  <section class="problem-section">
    <div class="problem-header">
      <span class="label-pill">Buyer's guide</span>
      <h2 class="h-lg">How to pick the right <span class="accent">social media scheduling tool.</span></h2>
      <p>If you're shopping outside this list, or if you're not sure which tool fits your situation, here's the decision framework we'd use ourselves.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="ba-grid">
      <div class="ba-col after" style="grid-column: 1 / -1;">
        <ul class="ba-list">
          <li>
            <span class="ba-num">01</span>
            <div>
              <h4>Decide first: do you want to schedule posts or have posts created for you?</h4>
              <p>Every tool on this list except theStacc requires you to write your own content. If you don't have time to write 30 posts per month, no scheduler solves that problem — only a done-for-you service does.</p>
            </div>
          </li>
          <li>
            <span class="ba-num">02</span>
            <div>
              <h4>Count your platforms and do the per-channel math before committing</h4>
              <p>Buffer at $6/channel sounds cheap until you're managing 10 accounts. Always calculate total monthly cost at your actual profile count, not just the entry price.</p>
            </div>
          </li>
          <li>
            <span class="ba-num">03</span>
            <div>
              <h4>Start with a free plan or $1 trial before committing to a paid tier</h4>
              <p>Buffer, Metricool, and Later all offer genuinely useful free plans. theStacc offers a $1 trial. Test the workflow before paying.</p>
            </div>
          </li>
          <li>
            <span class="ba-num">04</span>
            <div>
              <h4>Match the tool to your primary use case, not your secondary ones</h4>
              <p>Agorapulse is the best social inbox but costs 3x more than Sendible. SocialBee is the best evergreen recycler but has a steeper learning curve than Buffer. Don't pay for features you won't use weekly.</p>
            </div>
          </li>
          <li>
            <span class="ba-num">05</span>
            <div>
              <h4>Consider whether social media is a standalone channel or part of a broader SEO strategy</h4>
              <p>If you also need blog content and local SEO alongside social, theStacc's bundle (Blog SEO + Local SEO + Social) at 15% off is more cost-efficient than three separate tools.</p>
            </div>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

